From the Chair 3 On page 19 of this inspiring magazine you will see an item about our next Members’ Open Meeting. I am looking forward to being entertained by three of our musical groups, two of whom are celebrating their 10 year anniversary this year, and to sharing in their birthday cake! However we begin the meeting at 2 pm with our AGM, where your committee will be reporting on the overall situation of your u3a, and we will be electing the ofﬁcers and other trustees for this next 12 months. You will have received the formal papers last month, and they are available on our website at (https://u3aivo.uk/agm-2025). If you cannot actually come to the AGM in person but still want to play your part, you can vote by “proxy”. It is your way of being present and telling the chair how to place your votes. This year’s proxy form is attached with this magazine and available on the website. You need to get the signed form to the Secretary no later than 10am on Tuesday 9th September, either to 20 West Leys, St Ives, PE27 6DS, or secretarystivescambsu3a @gmail.com. We encourage proxy voting by any member who is unable to attend in person as this not only enables you to share in our decision- making, but also means you are included in the numbers that go towards the quorum for the meeting. Finally, thanks to everyone who has served on the committee this last year, to those who have offered to serve this next year, and to all members who play an active part in the life of our u3a. Peter Cooper, Chair Website: stivescambs.u3asite.uk or u3aivo.uk Email: chair@u3aivo.uk, if no email then call 07458 197372 A special welcome to our new Membership Secretary - Ian Brennand. Ian is a fairly new member and has offered to take on this key role, for which I am personally very grateful. Ian is hoping to be able to come to Members Open Meetings, so please do say hello when you see him. Peter

Free time to explore. £19 English Heritage members, £28 for Non Members Belton House (near Grantham) Monday 6th October Arrive mid-morning The day is free for you to explore the House and Gardens Sometimes described as the 'perfect' English country house estate, Belton was built in the late 17th century by 'Young' Sir John Brownlow. Home to the same family for nearly 300 years. Walking through the House you'll come across the Chapel Drawing Room, which is a rare example of decor that dates from the building of the house in 1683-1685 Cost (including Driver’s gratuity) National Trust members £17 Non-National Trust members £36

Group Support Team 9 We heard a comment recently that there are no new groups starting in u3a, so we would like to address this perception by reminding you of the groups started so far this year: AI Club All about the Art Casual Conversation Masters of Modern Art and Architecture Rummikub in the Garden Scrabble on the Move Strollers Tai Chi Friday Tai Chi Tuesday In addition, Genealogy just re- started in August, whilst Italian Beginners, Members On Their Own (MOTO) and Reading for Pleasure are all planning to start in September, but please note Italian Beginners is now full. Please check on their web pages to conﬁrm. All of our activities depend on members giving their time freely for the beneﬁt of fellow members, and we are very grateful to those members who have come forward to help in setting up these new groups, as well as all those who have continued to run their established groups. Unfortunately our Group Support Team is losing two members. Peter (Cooper) needs to step back in order to prioritise other responsibilities as Chair, and Peter (Law) is moving away. If we wish to continue expanding the range of interest groups available for members to join, we need new people to come forward and join our team. The aims of the GST are: 1) To liaise with and support existing groups as necessary (eg. when a leader is temporarily out of action, if there are any issues regarding venues, numbers etc) 2) To encourage and support new group ideas with advice about how to recruit members, convening an initial meeting, discussing possible venues, how to cover costs etc. Previous or current experience of running a group is helpful here, but not essential, as advice can be given. If you think you could join our team to help in this way, please contact us via the website here: https:// stivescambs.u3asite.uk/contact/ or come and speak to us at the Support Desk after an open meeting.

Spotlight on Walking 14 Our u3a now boasts three different walking groups that can offer a walking experience for everyone. This is good news for anyone wanting to get outside and enjoy a guided walk with friends or meet and make new friends. There is usually an opportunity for refreshment and social time at the end. All three groups have something special to offer and you can choose which group suits you best and try it out. Our leaders are a friendly team, passionate about walking and helping others access walking within a social setting. Country Walks The popular Country Walks group had been running for many years led by John and Lynda De Fries and when John said he needed to step down last September I was pleased to take over the reins with some help initially from John and continue to plan and provide this enjoyable monthly walk. The approach within this group is relaxed and open to all to just turn up on the morning of the walk. Details of each walk held on the fourth Wednesday of each month, except for August and December, can be found on the Country Walks u3a webpage. Our walks are approximately 6+ miles in length taking about two to two and half hours to complete and the aim is to go a little further aﬁeld to explore different villages and new routes. The time and distance can vary depending on the weather including heat as well as rain unsurprisingly these days. The webpage gives details of the starting point, time 10.00 am and a brief description of the walk including points of interest and terrain. Walkers come prepared for the weather and walking conditions and bring a light snack to revive us midway!
15 We also now have a group WhatsApp which allows us to share relevant details and comments and photos in real time and we encourage car sharing as much as possible. There are usually around 15 people on each walk. This is an ideal number who can keep together at a good pace and enjoy lots of conversation along the way. At the end of the walk it might be possible to enjoy a coffee or lunch in a local pub, although we are ﬁnding that more pubs are closed at lunchtime. A café or garden centre is another alternative or even a picnic weather permitting! Do get in contact with me if you would like to join in or try us out. https://stivescambs.u3asite.uk/ u3a_groups/country-walks/ Leisure Walks Our next group is Leisure Walks again a very popular group that has been running for many years led by Angela and Andrew Bouch. This friendly well established group meet up every two weeks on the ﬁrst and third Wednesday of the month. The name of the group again describes the ethos of the group, a little slower paced and a walk of between 3 and 4+ miles usually in the local vicinity but often with some interesting and unexpected ﬁnds along the way, such as churches and historical features in villages with plenty of time to catch up and chat to friends old and new. Refreshments at the end of these walks is an important aspect of the group experience. Please get in touch if you would like to join, Angela sends out a regular email with the walk details.
Spotlight on Walking 16 https://stivescambs.u3asite.uk/ u3a_groups/leisure-walks/ Strollers Finally we reach our newest group Strollers. This group grew out of a need for a much slower paced and shorter walk to provide an opportunity for those in need of this to get out and about. Many people signed up to the idea of this new group at the u3a Open Day and met up in the Golden Lion for coffee and a chance to discuss the needs of members and how the group could work. 15 members met in Somersham on Monday 23 rd June to take a gentle walk around the local Nature Reserve and then drove around to Parkhall garden centre for a coffee and debrief. This proved a successful start and we now have leaders Roger and Sophie Brown working alongside myself and with help from Angela to make this a regular meet up on the second and fourth Monday of the month. Safety in the form of avoiding any spills or accidents out strolling is very important amongst this group and I have strongly suggested that people joining in with this group will need walking poles. All walkers should use walking poles as they add to stability by providing the walker with four points of contact with the ground and they take a lot of stress away from knee and hip joints. They also give the arms and upper body a good work out. Please consider getting yourself a pair possibly from Mountain Warehouse or on Amazon, you will be delighted with the improvement in your walking and we can avoid any potential accidents. https://stivescambs.u3asite.uk/ u3a_groups/strollers/ I hope you have found this round up of u3a walking interesting and hope to meet you soon. Gill Jones
Poem by Jennifer Colville 17 Crutches Have you ever been on crutches? Well, it really is a bore, you cannot use either of your hands but your hands get very sore! They want you to use them for the stairs, that’s so dangerous with every tread, just a tiny loss of balance a trip, and you can end up dead. I just do the stairs upon my bum, much safer that for everyone!! Every time you put them down they slide off across the ﬂoor, then, try to bend to pick them up, well, that hurts even more! The dog she really hates them, Mum can’t take her out for walks, also, Mum can’t pick her up with one leg and two metal stalks!! You cannot do the garden, the weeds are growing fast, the hoe is no good as a crutch, the re-wilding area is vast. The house, well that’s just gone to pot, the husband cannot do the lot, he tries to wear a household mask, but shouts, “how do you multi task”? A few more days and they’ll be gone, just hope the surgeons job is done!!! Jennifer 31 st May 2025

Members’ Open Meeting 11th September Our Members’ Open Meeting on Thursday 11 th September will begin at 2pm with our AGM and you have already been sent notice of this meeting, along with relevant papers. It is anticipated this will be a short meeting, mainly to appoint ofﬁcers and trustees for another year, and to receive last year’s ﬁnancial report. We are delighted that our Jazz Combo group have agreed to play from 1.20pm that day, as members arrive, and once the formal business is concluded, it will be time for a celebration! A lot of our u3a groups have been established for many years and may already have passed milestone birthdays. However, Singing for Pleasure and Uke-Troupe were both started in 2015, so are celebrating 10 th birthdays this year. It was suggested a while ago that our AGM would be an opportunity for both groups to come together and provide some entertainment. Both groups will perform some songs from their repertoires, and there will also be some songs for audience participation—and of course, no birthday would be complete without cake! Do come along to show your support at the AGM for those who give their time voluntarily throughout the year to run our u3a, and join us in celebrating all the activities that many of us are able to enjoy. Many of you will be aware that emails you receive as u3a members have been sent using our Beacon system. These could be the monthly magazine or newsletter, general messages sometimes from me on behalf of others, or from your group leader. It is usually possible to reply to the person who sent it, just by hitting “Reply”, but it seems this may not always work when using an i-phone or i-pad, as there can be variation in the way these devices have been set up. If you wish to reply to an email sent via Beacon, please bear in mind the following advice: Hit Reply (not Reply All), and when the new email window opens: 1) Check that the address at the top in the To: line is the person you expect 2) Ensure it does not say noreply@u3abeacon.org.uk 3) If it does, delete that address and look for the address at the very bottom of the email you received where it says, “This email was sent by Beacon on behalf of … “ and put that address in the To: line of your reply instead of the “no reply@ … “ address. Thank you to the member who drew this possible problem to our attention, as it was an issue we had not previously been aware of. Joy Cooper (Beacon Administrator) 19 Replying to Emails sent via Beacon
